BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:LTwlYr7aMp6r3HdUmMlkL
SUMMARY:Earth Month Event | Restoration at Ellis Pond
DTSTAMP:20260407T043746Z
DTSTART:20260411T163000Z
DESCRIPTION:Celebrate Earth Month at our Ellis Pond Work Party\n\nJoin us  
	at Ellis Pond Park for a Forest-Steward led weeding and clean-up event fo 
	r Earth Month. Removing certain plants will help build even more wildlife 
	 habitat in this small neighborhood park teeming with birds and other wood
	l and creatures. We will remove weeds like English ivy\, Himalayan blackbe
	rry\, and English holly to help protect native plants and forest health. C
	ome join friends and neighbors in this fun Saturday event.  \n\nNo experie
	 nce necessary\; gloves and tools are provided. Participation is limited\,
	 so please register.\n\nPlease note: we require participants aged 14 and  
	under to volunteer with a parent or guardian at a ratio of 1 adult to 3 ki
	 ds.\n\nWhen: Saturday\, April 11th\, 9:30am-11:30pm\n\nWhere: Ellis Pond 
	Park \\(meet at the bench next to the boardwalk on 90th Ave SE\\)\n\nWhat 
	to bring:  Dress for the weather in clothes you don't mind getting dirty \
	\(think: lon g pants\, boots or sneakers\\). Bring a water bottle. Small s
	nacks\, gloves\, and tools will be provided. And a snack or dish to share.
	 \n\nRegistration : volunteersignup.org/Y8XQX\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.
	com/events/#/details/earth-month-event-restoration-at-ellis-pond/18066408/
	2026-04-11T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Sports & Outdoors
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/earth-month-event-restora
	tion-at-ellis-pond/18066408/2026-04-11T00
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-sports
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Sports & Outdoors
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT2H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:mBTSgG-2WEm2wCSUfbfu1
SUMMARY:Foraging for Basketry and Wild Crafts
DTSTAMP:20260407T043746Z
DTSTART:20260411T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:Taught by basket maker and teacher Erin Cox. Join the conversat
	ion about the incredible plants that grow here in the Pacific Northwest an
	d explore ways to identify\, gather\, store and use them to create baskets
	 and crafts that bring nature inside. Whether you live in an urban\, subur
	ban or rural setting\, there are forage-able crafting and weaving material
	s to be found. Daylily\, daffodil\, dandelion\, crocosmia\, iris\, cattail
	s\, juncus\, bulrush\, ivy\, honeysuckle\, wisteria\, dogwood\, willow and
	 more! Erin will share about her approach to sustainable and responsible f
	oraging. We should all care for the plants we harvest and preserve the env
	ironments they grow in. This discussion is good for beginners and you will
	 walk away with some fun\, easy ways to get started. $17.50 BBGS Member/$2
	5 Non-Member \n\nErin found her life’s passion in basketry and wild crafti
	ng. In 2024 she established a small basketry willow farm in Carnation\, Wa
	shington\, where she invites students to learn\, harvest\, and engage with
	 the materials. In 2025\, she opened Field and Forest Crafts and her own p
	rivate teaching studio in NE Seattle.\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/even
	ts/#/details/foraging-for-basketry-and-wild-crafts/18185398/2026-04-11T00\
	n\nFrom SEAtoday - Sports & Outdoors
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/foraging-for-basketry-and
	-wild-crafts/18185398/2026-04-11T00
LOCATION:Bellevue Botanical Garden\, 12001 Main St\, Bellevue\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-sports
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Sports & Outdoors
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT2H
END:VEVENT
